{"title_page": "Jeni Couzyn", "text_new": "{{Infobox person|image= |caption= |birth_date=1942|birth_place=[[South Africa]]|occupation=poet and anthologist|known_for=''[[Life by Drowning: Selected Poems]]''}}\n'''Jeni Couzyn''' (born 1942) is a [[List of feminist poets|feminist poet]] and [[anthologist]] of South African extraction who lives and works in Canada and the United Kingdom. Her best known collection is titled ''[[Life by Drowning: Selected Poems]]'' (1985), which includes an earlier sequence ''A Time to Be Born'' (1981) that chronicles her pregnancy and the birth of her daughter.<ref name=\"OUP\">{{cite web|title=The Oxford Companion to Twentieth-Century Literature in English|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780192122711.001.0001/acref-9780192122711-e-588|editor= Jenny Stringer|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref name= Lampert>{{cite book|last1= Couzyn|first1= Jeni|last2= Sullivan|first2= Rosemary|author-link2= Rosemary Sullivan|editor1-last= Lampert|editor1-first= Arlene|title=The Selected Poems of Jeni Couzyn|url={{Google books|iTUg-QEP1tcC|The Selected Poems of Jeni Couzyn|page=219|plainurl= yes}}|year=2006|publisher=Exile Editions|pages=xi-xiii|isbn=978-1550965384}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jeni Couzyn|url=http://orlando.cambridge.org/public/svPeople?person_id=couzje|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nCouzyn was born in South Africa and educated at the [[University of Natal]]. She emigrated to Britain in 1966 and established herself as a freelance writer. She became a Canadian citizen in 1975 and the following year was appointed writer-in-residence at the [[University of Victoria]], British Columbia. Since then she has divided her time between England, Canada, and South Africa.<ref name=\"Columbia\">{{cite book|title=The Columbia Guide to South African Literature in English Since 1945|date=2010|publisher=[[Columbia University Press]]|isbn=978-0231130462|url={{Google books|j2j_ieNDsU4C|The Columbia Guide to South African Literature in English Since 1945|page=78|plainurl= yes}}}}</ref>\n\n== Work ==\n\n=== Poetry ===\nCouzyn's first collection was titled ''Flying'' (1970). Later collections include ''Christmas in Africa'' (1975), ''A Time to be Born'' (1981), ''Life by Drowning: Selected poems'' (1985), and ''That's It'' (1993).<ref name= S145>Stringer p. 145</ref>\n\n''A Time to be Born'' deals with childbirth from \"conception to birth and early infancy\".<ref name=\"Papke\">{{cite book|last1=Papke|first1=Renate|title=Poems at the Edge of Differences: Mothering in New English Poetry by Women|date=2010|publisher=University Of Akron Press|isbn=1931968810|url={{Google books|A2ayKA7Dq8EC|Poems at the Edge of Differences: Mothering in New English Poetry by Women|page=183|plainurl= yes}}}}</ref>\n\n''The Oxford Companion to Twentieth-Century Literature in English'' remarks that Couzyn's poetry repeatedly engages the social, political and imaginative implications of womanhood. Her poetry has been described as minimalist. The ''Oxford Companion'' observes that her conception of poetry as pre-eminently oral gives much of her work clarity and immediacy.<ref name= S145/><ref name = P183>Papke p. 183</ref>\n\n=== Anthologies ===\nCouzyn edited the influential ''[[Bloodaxe Books#Women poets|The Bloodaxe Book of Contemporary Women Poets]]'' (1985), set as an [[A-level]] text in British schools at the time. A later anthology, ''Singing Down the Bones'' (1989), was aimed at a teenage audience.<ref name= S145/><ref name=\"Childs\">{{cite book|last1=Childs|first1=Peter|title=The Twentieth Century in Poetry|date=1998|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0415171016|url={{Google books|mC6EAgAAQBAJ|The Twentieth Century in Poetry|page=164|plainurl= yes}}}}</ref>\n\n=== Other ===\nCouzyn has authored two books for children. With Julie Malgas, she produced a study of [[Koos Malgas]], the sculptor who helped create ''[[The Owl House]]'', a [[museum]] in [[Nieu-Bethesda]], [[Eastern Cape]], [[South Africa]], noted for its visionary conception.<ref name=\"Malgas\">{{cite book|last1=Malgas|first1=Julia|last2=Couzyn|first2=Jeni|title=Koos Malgas, sculptor of the Owl House|date=2008|publisher=Firelizard|location=Nieu Bethesda|isbn=9780953505821}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links[edit] ==\n\n* [https://findingaids.library.columbia.edu/ead/nnc-rb/ldpd_4078656 Finding aid to Jeni Couzyn papers at Columbia University. Rare Book & Manuscript Library.]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Couzyn, Jeni}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:Canadian women poets]]\n[[Category:Canadian feminist writers]]\n[[Category:Women anthologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:South African women poets]]\n[[Category:South African feminists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person|image= |caption= |birth_date=1942|birth_place=[[South Africa]]|occupation=poet and anthologist|known_for=''[[Life by Drowning: Selected Poems]]''}}\n'''Jeni Couzyn''' (born 1942) is a [[List of feminist poets|feminist poet]] and [[anthologist]] of South African extraction who lives and works in Canada and the United Kingdom. Her best known collection is titled ''[[Life by Drowning: Selected Poems]]'' (1985), which includes an earlier sequence ''A Time to Be Born'' (1981) that chronicles her pregnancy and the birth of her daughter.<ref name=\"OUP\">{{cite web|title=The Oxford Companion to Twentieth-Century Literature in English|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780192122711.001.0001/acref-9780192122711-e-588|editor= Jenny Stringer|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref name= Lampert>{{cite book|last1= Couzyn|first1= Jeni|last2= Sullivan|first2= Rosemary|author-link2= Rosemary Sullivan|editor1-last= Lampert|editor1-first= Arlene|title=The Selected Poems of Jeni Couzyn|url={{Google books|iTUg-QEP1tcC|The Selected Poems of Jeni Couzyn|page=219|plainurl= yes}}|year=2006|publisher=Exile Editions|pages=xi-xiii|isbn=978-1550965384}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jeni Couzyn|url=http://orlando.cambridge.org/public/svPeople?person_id=couzje|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nCouzyn was born in South Africa and educated at the [[University of Natal]]. She emigrated to Britain in 1966 and established herself as a freelance writer. She became a Canadian citizen in 1975 and the following year was appointed writer-in-residence at the [[University of Victoria]], British Columbia. Since then she has divided her time between England, Canada, and South Africa.<ref name=\"Columbia\">{{cite book|title=The Columbia Guide to South African Literature in English Since 1945|date=2010|publisher=[[Columbia University Press]]|isbn=978-0231130462|url={{Google books|j2j_ieNDsU4C|The Columbia Guide to South African Literature in English Since 1945|page=78|plainurl= yes}}}}</ref>\n\n== Work ==\n\n=== Poetry ===\nCouzyn's first collection was titled ''Flying'' (1970). Later collections include ''Christmas in Africa'' (1975), ''A Time to be Born'' (1981), ''Life by Drowning: Selected poems'' (1985), and ''That's It'' (1993).<ref name= S145>Stringer p. 145</ref>\n\n''A Time to be Born'' deals with childbirth from \"conception to birth and early infancy\".<ref name=\"Papke\">{{cite book|last1=Papke|first1=Renate|title=Poems at the Edge of Differences: Mothering in New English Poetry by Women|date=2010|publisher=University Of Akron Press|isbn=1931968810|url={{Google books|A2ayKA7Dq8EC|Poems at the Edge of Differences: Mothering in New English Poetry by Women|page=183|plainurl= yes}}}}</ref>\n\n''The Oxford Companion to Twentieth-Century Literature in English'' remarks that Couzyn's poetry repeatedly engages the social, political and imaginative implications of womanhood. Her poetry has been described as minimalist. The ''Oxford Companion'' observes that her conception of poetry as pre-eminently oral gives much of her work clarity and immediacy.<ref name= S145/><ref name = P183>Papke p. 183</ref>\n\n=== Anthologies ===\nCouzyn edited the influential ''[[Bloodaxe Books#Women poets|The Bloodaxe Book of Contemporary Women Poets]]'' (1985), set as an [[A-level]] text in British schools at the time. A later anthology, ''Singing Down the Bones'' (1989), was aimed at a teenage audience.<ref name= S145/><ref name=\"Childs\">{{cite book|last1=Childs|first1=Peter|title=The Twentieth Century in Poetry|date=1998|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0415171016|url={{Google books|mC6EAgAAQBAJ|The Twentieth Century in Poetry|page=164|plainurl= yes}}}}</ref>\n\n=== Other ===\nCouzyn has authored two books for children. With Julie Malgas, she produced a study of [[Koos Malgas]], the sculptor who helped create ''[[The Owl House]]'', a [[museum]] in [[Nieu-Bethesda]], [[Eastern Cape]], [[South Africa]], noted for its visionary conception.<ref name=\"Malgas\">{{cite book|last1=Malgas|first1=Julia|last2=Couzyn|first2=Jeni|title=Koos Malgas, sculptor of the Owl House|date=2008|publisher=Firelizard|location=Nieu Bethesda|isbn=9780953505821}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Couzyn, Jeni}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:Canadian women poets]]\n[[Category:Canadian feminist writers]]\n[[Category:Women anthologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:South African women poets]]\n[[Category:South African feminists]]\n", "name_user": "Hazzardcu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeni_Couzyn"}
